ADDING ENEMIES

Answer: Freeing Enemy Memory
‚úÖ Yes, free(game->enemies); is enough to free the allocated memory for enemies.
üö® You do NOT need free_list() because:
free_list() is designed for freeing linked lists (t_map *map), but we are using an array (t_coord *enemies).
An array only needs free(game->enemies); to release the allocated block.
Since enemies is dynamically allocated with malloc(), a single free() is sufficient.

üìå Enemy Implementation Summary for Documentation
üîπ Why Use an Array for Enemies?
We store enemy positions in a dynamically allocated array (t_coord *enemies) inside t_game.
Since the number of enemies is fixed and known at game start (from the .ber map file), an array is the most efficient choice.

‚úÖ Advantages of Using an Array
‚úî Faster access: Each enemy‚Äôs position is accessed instantly using indexing (enemies[i]).
‚úî Less memory overhead: Unlike a linked list, an array does not require extra pointers for each element.
‚úî Easier to iterate: The for/while loop directly accesses elements, making movement simpler.

‚ùå Disadvantages of Using an Array
‚úñ Fixed size: The array size is determined at game start and cannot dynamically grow or shrink.
‚úñ Memory allocation upfront: We must allocate memory for all enemies at once, even if some are removed later.

üîπ Functions for Enemy Implementation
üìå 1. find_enemies()
üìç Purpose: Finds all enemy ('X') positions in the map and stores them in game->enemies.

üìç Breakdown:
‚úÖ Calls count_enemies(game); to count how many enemies exist.
‚úÖ Allocates memory for the enemies array (malloc(sizeof(t_coord) * enemy_count)).
‚úÖ Calls store_enemies(game); to save each enemy's (x, y) position in the array.

üìç Why is this needed?

Ensures all enemies are tracked in memory so they can move.
Runs once at game start.
üìå 2. count_enemies()
üìç Purpose: Scans the map and counts the total number of enemies ('X').

üìç Breakdown:
‚úÖ Loops through game->array_map using while loops.
‚úÖ Increments game->enemy_count for every 'X' found.

üìç Why is this needed?

Determines how much memory to allocate for game->enemies.
üìå 3. store_enemies()
üìç Purpose: Stores each enemy‚Äôs position in the game->enemies array.

üìç Breakdown:
‚úÖ Iterates through game->array_map using while loops.
‚úÖ Saves (x, y) coordinates of each enemy in game->enemies[count].

üìç Why is this needed?

Ensures enemies remember their positions so they can move.
üìå 4. move_enemies()
üìç Purpose: Moves each enemy left or right (if possible) every frame.

üìç Breakdown:
‚úÖ Loops through game->enemies using while.
‚úÖ Checks if the left position is free (FLOOR), moves left if true.
‚úÖ If left is blocked, checks the right position (FLOOR) and moves right.
‚úÖ Calls update_enemy_pos(game, i, new_x, new_y); to update the enemy‚Äôs position.

üìç Why is this needed?

Moves enemies automatically every frame inside render_frame().
If an enemy reaches the player, the game ends immediately.
üìå 5. update_enemy_pos()
üìç Purpose: Updates enemy position in game->array_map and detects player collision.

üìç Breakdown:
‚úÖ If the new position contains PJ, game over (close_handler()).
‚úÖ Updates game->array_map to move the enemy.
‚úÖ Updates game->enemies[i] with new (x, y).

üìç Why is this needed?

Keeps movement logic separate from decision-making (move_enemies()).
Prevents map corruption by ensuring enemies update correctly.
üìå 6. Freeing Enemy Memory in close_window()
üìç Purpose: Frees the dynamically allocated game->enemies array when the game exits.

üìç Breakdown:
‚úÖ If game->enemies is not NULL, call free(game->enemies);.

üìç Why is this needed?

Prevents memory leaks when the game closes.
üîπ How Everything Works Together
Game Start (game_start())
1Ô∏è‚É£ Find all enemies ‚Üí find_enemies().
2Ô∏è‚É£ Store their positions ‚Üí store_enemies().
3Ô∏è‚É£ Enemies are now tracked in game->enemies[].

During the Game (render_frame())
1Ô∏è‚É£ Enemies move every frame ‚Üí move_enemies().
2Ô∏è‚É£ Each enemy updates its position ‚Üí update_enemy_pos().
3Ô∏è‚É£ If an enemy reaches the player, the game ends.

Game Exit
1Ô∏è‚É£ Memory is freed ‚Üí free(game->enemies);.

üéØ Summary of Implementation
‚úî Enemies are stored in an array (t_coord *enemies).
‚úî They move left or right in move_enemies().
‚úî If they touch the player, game over.
‚úî Memory is properly freed at game exit.
=====================================================

Understanding the Flickering Issue
From what you described, the issue is likely happening because all images are being re-rendered on every frame without double buffering.
üìå Possible causes of the flicker:

mlx_clear_window() in render_frame() (in mlx_load_render.c)
This clears everything before redrawing, which can cause a visible flicker.
Lack of double buffering
MiniLibX does not use double buffering by default.
Each frame is drawn directly to the window, making rendering appear unstable.
Inefficient Redrawing
The game re-renders the entire screen even when only a small portion has changed.
Solution: Enable Double Buffering
How?
Instead of drawing directly on the screen, draw everything to an "off-screen" image (buffer) first.
Once the entire frame is ready, copy it to the window in one step.
This avoids flickering caused by clearing and redrawing partial images.
Implementation Plan
Modify t_game to add a back buffer (an off-screen image).
Render everything to the buffer instead of the window.
Display the fully rendered buffer in one go.


